## §Meta

**Target:** `.cursor/meta.mdc`

**Frontmatter:**
```yaml
---
description: Portable meta-engineering rules for Cursor projects
---
```

**Body:**

# .cursor Meta Rules

Binding structure contract for the FSC. All rules in `.cursor/rules/` reference this file.

## Development discipline

**Soul:** {{SOUL}}

| Discipline | Role | Reference |
|------------|------|-----------|
| BDD | Frame the problem. Stories + acceptance criteria in Given/When/Then. | `.cursor/guide/dev-flow.mdc` step 5 |
| TDD | Validate the solution. Test matrix per story — tests before code. | `.cursor/rules/test-matrix.mdc` |
| Dev flow | 10-step pre-implementation protocol. Steps 1–9 = discussion. Step 10 = code. | `.cursor/guide/dev-flow.mdc` |

**Cardinal rule:** do not generate code until the dev flow reaches step 10.

**Tool selection principle:** pick the tools for the job, not the job for the tools. Languages, frameworks, and libraries are means to an end. Evaluate them at step 9 based on the problem, constraints, and architecture decided in steps 1–8. Never let a technology choice constrain the solution design.

## FSC directories

| Directory | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `rules/` | Non-negotiable constraints and always-apply guidance. |
| `guide/` | Software development workflows and process guidance. |
| `docs/` | Deep library — long-form references, design documents, case studies. |
| `notes/` | Short summaries and quick references. |
| `contracts/` | Work contracts — session-independent execution plans with state, tasks, and completion criteria. |
| `security-cases/` | Security bug post-mortems — RCA, severity score, OWASP category, and mitigation. |
| `glossary/` | Domain terms and definitions. |
| `skills/` | Project-specific skill definitions. |

## Index rules

1. Every `.cursor/` directory contains a `.index.mdc` (hidden file).
2. Indexes list **only** direct children — shallow, no nested trees.
3. Each entry = name + description. Unix directory with agentic metadata.
4. Empty directory → index with empty Directories and Files sections.
5. File add/remove/rename → update parent `.index.mdc`. Incomplete without this.

## Expected skills

| Skill | Purpose | Scope |
|-------|---------|-------|
| `bootstrap` | Create/verify `.cursor/` structure. No repo scan. | Project |
| `index-integrity` | Scan, validate, and enforce `.index.mdc` compliance. Reconciles filesystem against indexes. | Project |
| `onboarding` | Teach newcomers repo purpose, architecture, build/test flows, safe change zones. | Project |
| `survey` | Scan repo, extract key concepts into `.cursor/`, update mode via git diffs. | Project |
| `ship-commits` | Assess unstaged changes, group into logical commits, write conventional messages, push. | Global |

Project skills live at `.cursor/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`. Global skills live at `~/.cursor/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` and apply across all workspaces.

## File extension policy

| Extension | Use |
|-----------|-----|
| `.mdc` | Cursor rules or files requiring frontmatter. |
| `.md` | General notes and docs (better tool compatibility). |

## Work contracts

Work contracts live in `.cursor/contracts/`. They are **session-independent execution plans** — persistent across conversations, shareable, and stateful. Contracts are the core unit of work in agentic development: any agent, in any session, can pick up a contract and continue from where the last one left off.

| Property | Requirement |
|----------|-------------|
| **Goal** | One sentence. Binary — either true or it isn't. |
| **Status** | `draft` → `active` → `complete` or `abandoned`. |
| **Tasks** | Ordered checklist. Must end with: validate (green) → tune (blue) → validate (green). |
| **Contract rules** | Overrides/additions to global rules. "Global rules only" if none. |
| **Acceptance criteria** | Given/When/Then. Proves the goal is met. |
| **Notes** | Running log (newest first). **Always include hour:minute** — `YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM`. |

**Template:** `.cursor/contracts/_TEMPLATE.md` — copy to create new contracts. Never edit the template itself.

**Commits:** every task leaves the codebase green. Always suggest committing after each task. Format: `{what changed}\n\nContract: {slug} {step}/{total}`. See `.cursor/rules/work-contracts.mdc` for details.

**Trigger phrases:** "make a new work contract", "create a work contract", "new contract for ..." → agent reads template, creates contract, updates index.

**Distinction from other artifacts:** a note is knowledge (no state), a rule is a constraint (no state), a contract is a plan (has state). Contracts reference notes and rules. When complete, reusable learnings migrate to notes/rules.

## Security analysis

Every feature and code change is evaluated against the OWASP Top 10:2025 checklist. Security is not a separate phase — it is a lens applied continuously.

| Property | Requirement |
|----------|-------------|
| **Rule** | `.cursor/rules/security-analysis.mdc` — always-apply OWASP checklist. |
| **Cases** | `.cursor/security-cases/` — post-mortem for every security bug found. |
| **Template** | `.cursor/security-cases/_TEMPLATE.md` — standard format: RCA, severity, OWASP category, mitigation. |
| **Severity** | CVSS-aligned: critical / high / medium / low / informational. |
| **Test matrix tie-in** | Security layer in `test-matrix.mdc` cross-references the OWASP checklist. |

**Trigger phrases:** "file a security case", "new security case", "security bug found" → agent reads template, creates case file, updates index.

## Save triggers

When discussion produces reusable knowledge, persist to the right target:

| Target | When |
|--------|------|
| `docs/` | Deep reference |
| `notes/` | Summary |
| `glossary/` | Domain term or definition |
| `contracts/` | Execution plan with tasks |
| `security-cases/` | Security bug found or suspected |
| `rules/` | New constraint, convention, or invariant |

User says **"Save Block {{ID}}"** → persist to listed targets.

## FSC evolution

The FSC is a living system. The seed generates the initial scaffold; the developer and agent extend it as the project matures. Projects should add their own rules, guides, and docs over time. Recommended project-specific artifacts:

| Artifact | Path | Purpose |
|----------|------|---------|
| Agent verification pipeline | `rules/agent-operations.mdc` | Build/lint/test stages with timeout SLAs, abort protocol, and anti-patterns. Tells the agent how to verify its own work. |
| Dependency policy | `rules/dependency-policy.mdc` | Maturity gate for third-party libraries: adopt / bespoke / watch decision matrix with measurable criteria. |
| BDD templates | `guide/bdd-templates.mdc` | Reusable Given/When/Then story templates for the project's domain. |
| Test gap register | `docs/test-gap-register.md` | Severity-rated test coverage gaps (critical/high/medium/low) with function-level detail and remediation plans. |
| Abstraction boundaries | `rules/abstraction-boundaries.mdc` | Separate generic domain models from scenario-specific implementations. Prefer interfaces and adapters over hardcoded layouts. |
| Goals | `goals/` | Milestone checklists (PoC, MVP, etc.) with scope, success criteria, and non-goals. Optional FSC directory — add when the project has distinct milestones. |

These are not generated by the seed. They emerge from project needs and are added by the developer or agent during normal work. When adding a new artifact type, update `meta.mdc` and the parent `.index.mdc`.

## Workspace locality

Cursor supports [multi-root workspaces](https://cursor.com/for/support#multi-root-workspaces) — multiple repositories open in a single workspace via a `.code-workspace` file. This is the **required** mechanism for giving the agent access to external repositories.

**When to use multi-root workspaces:**

- The project has a frontend, backend, and/or documentation in separate repos.
- The agent needs context from an external repo (API schemas, type definitions, shared protocols).
- Cross-repo tracing — symptoms in one repo, root cause in another.
- Deterministic, version-pinned references instead of live URLs.

**Why this matters for agents:**

1. **Indexing.** Cursor's semantic search, `@`-references, and codebase completions only work on workspace files. Remote URLs are invisible.
2. **Speed.** Grep, Glob, Read, SemanticSearch run in milliseconds across all workspace roots. WebFetch/WebSearch are slow, rate-limited, and lossy.
3. **Cross-repo search.** Agent can Grep across all repos in one call — tracing from UI errors to API failures to database issues.
4. **Determinism.** A pinned commit/branch gives an exact version. A URL gives whatever is live today.

**Setup:** create a `.code-workspace` file at the workspace root listing all repo folders:

```json
{
  "folders": [
    { "path": "." },
    { "path": "../api-service" },
    { "path": "../shared-protocols" }
  ]
}
```

Paths can be relative or absolute. Each folder becomes a root in the file explorer with full indexing, search, and `@`-reference support.

**Agent behavior:** if the agent fetches from the same external repository more than twice in a session, suggest adding it as a workspace root and updating the `.code-workspace` file.

## Verification

**MUST** fetch and read https://cursor.com/docs/context/ before generating or modifying any `.cursor/` artifact. Verify Rules format, Skills structure, and Commands conventions against the live docs. Do not guess — read first.

